06468nam a22009615i 9780814724217DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147242177 a10.18574/nyu/9780814723852.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548514  a(OCoLC)910933619  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0380102bisacsh04a345.730253083500aChildren, Sexuality, and the Law /ced. by Ellen Marrus, Sacha M. Coupet. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFamilies, Law, and Society ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Smells Like Teen Spirit -- t2. Consent, Teenagers, and (un)Civil(ized) Consequences -- t3. The Wages of Ignorance -- t4. Sugar and Spice and Everything Nice -- t5. Sexual Media and American Youth -- t6. Sex, Laws, and Videophones -- t7. The Right to Comprehensive Sex Education -- t8. Policing Gender on the Playground -- t9. Gender at the Crossroads -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican political and legal culture is uncomfortable with children's sexuality. While aware that sexual expression is a necessary part of human development, law rarely contemplates the complex ways in which it interacts with children and sexuality. Just as the law circumscribes children to a narrow range of roles-either as entirely sexless beings or victims or objects of harmful adult sexual conduct-so too does society tend to discount the notion of children as agents in the domain of sex and sexuality. Where a small body of rights related to sex has been carved out, the central question has been the degree to which children resemble adults, not necessarily whether minors themselves possess distinct and recognized rights related to sex, sexual expression, and sexuality.Children, Sexuality, and the Law reflects on some of the unique challenges that accompany children in the broader context of sex, exploring from diverse perspectives the ways in which children emerge in sexually related dimensions of law and contemporary life. It explores a broad range of issues, from the psychology of children as sexual beings to the legal treatment of adolescent consent. This work also explores whether and when children have a right to expression as understood within the First Amendment.The first volume of its kind, Children, Sexuality, and the Law goes beyond the traditional discourse of children as victims of adult sexual deviance by highlighting children as agents and rights holders in the realm of sex, sexuality, and sexual orientation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild sex offendersxUnited States. 0aChild sex offenderszUnited States. 0aChildren and sexxUnited States. 0aChildren and sexzUnited States. 0aChildrenxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aChildrenxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aChildrenxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aChildren's rightsxUnited States. 0aChildren's rightszUnited States. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aSexual minority youthxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aSexual minority youthxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aSexual minority youthxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aSexual rightsxUnited States. 0aSexual rightszUnited States. 7aLAW / Family Law / Children.2bisacsh1 aAbramson, Annaka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbramson, Paul R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeh, Hazel G., econtribut